aling to deliver millions of tons to orbit per year.\n\n**Timelines**\n*   **Initial Deployment:** The company expects to begin deploying its orbital AI compute satellites **as early as 2028**.\n*   **Scaling:** The company intends to deploy orbital AI compute "at scale" by the **end of the decade**.\n\n**Forward-Looking Statements & Strategy**\n*   **Overcoming Terrestrial Constraints:** The company projects that the $26.5 trillion AI market will be constrained by Earth\'s inability to rapidly scale power generation. Moving power-intensive AI workloads (like inference) into Sun-synchronous orbit leverages near-constant, uninterrupted solar energy, which the company views as the "only truly scalable solution to terrestrial energy constraints."\n*   **Cost Efficiency:** By combining unlimited solar power with its low-cost launch capabilities and satellite manufacturing, the company believes orbital data centers can eventually achieve a "fundamentally lower cost structure than is possible on Earth," accelerating time to power and reducing token costs.\n*   **Leveraging Terrestrial Expertise:** The company plans to use its rapid terrestrial data center deployment experience (like the COLOSSUS facilities) to package AI compute into modular, satellite form factors. It plans to subject hardware to extensive pre-deployment testing on Earth and use existing Starlink fleet management software to reallocate traffic and prevent cluster-level downtime if hardware fails in orbit.\n*   **Connectivity:** Starlink will provide low-latency, global connectivity linking orbital AI systems to Earth, while a dynamic mesh network of over 23,000 inter-satellite lasers will route traffic through orbit rather than relying solely on terrestrial backhaul.\n*   **Competitive Moat:** The company asserts it is the "only company with a commercially viable path to building orbital AI compute at scale," citing its extreme vertical integration across launch, satellite manufacturing, network connectivity, and terrestrial data center expertise. It notes that Starlink satellites have already demonstrated 99.9% average uptime and launch survivability.\n*   **Key Risks:** The strategy is subject to significant technical complexity, regulatory approvals, and the successful commercial development of Starship. The company explicitly warns that if Starship faces significant delays, its ability to deploy orbital AI infrastructure at scale would be "materially and adversely affected." Additionally, it cautions that emerging markets for orbital AI may not develop as expected, particularly if terrestrial data centers sufficiently meet future AI compute demand.',
